Say what you will about "humanising the despicable". All I see is that the writers seem to be more interested in telling the story of rapists and domestic abusers (videogame example) before telling the story of the victims and survivors, those who actually need to comforted.

The story portrays this as a past mistake, but it felt incredibly tactless. One doesn't simply rape someone one day. It isn't just a drunken mistake of a reckless young man. Trashing a temple is, that was good enough.

That made sense for what had been established for the character, but for some reason, the writer felt the need to make him a fucking rapist. To turn this character we had grown to see a nice but troubled man into a nightmare that specially affects women.

He knowingly enabled this, simply because that same monster was in the shape of a beautiful woman who seemed to like him despite his beastly appearance. That was already a good twist. That in his own weakness of mind, he enabled a massacre just to not be lonely.

On paper, it might seem like an ingenious twist, but there was already a perfectly good twist on his morality. After being teased throughout the episode, we find out he had been sheltering a monster that had been killing the entire neighbouring village.

By the end of the episode, we find out he actually raped the priestess and that's the real reason why she cursed him. We spend the entire episode sympathising with him, feeling bad for his loneliness, his bad mental health and past suicide attempts.

In the first episode of the season, we get a male character who we are meant to see as endearing and charming. He speaks of his curse of eternal loneliness and how it fell upon him because of this one time he trashed a temple and its priestess cursed him to look like a beast.

I've seen many fans of The Witcher (both the third videogame and the show) praise it for its "transgressive" humanisation of despicable characters. Specifically, male characters who partake in misogynistic violence. A recent example is in the second season of the show.
Anyways, that's a wrap, I'm gonna go check if the Lana Wachowski has actually done any other good films or if the Matrix was just a glitch in the simulation (okay, mean joke but I had to).

And to add one last thing, the movie tries to pull a bunch of self-aware jokes on the franchise with the new simulation’s design, but it feels more like lampshading than actual self-awareness. There's no point in being self-aware if you are gonna make those same mistakes.

The movie didn't feature the green tint, which is fine but they didn't really do anything stylistically to compensate. At moments the movie felt as visually bland as Avengers Endgame (at least then it sorta works for the comedic tone).

The song gave the leather-bearing grunge vibe I love from the earlier movies, but this one didn't even earn it. There's no other point where the movie actually delves into that style (save for the first scene which is just a flashback to the first movie).

The movie ends with Trinity being a girlboss and flying off frame while holding hands with Neo and a bomb-ass grunge song playing. That last frame was one of the three moments of photography that actually made me feel something, and it was mostly cuz the song was fire.

And then they go to the Matrix to try to get Trinity too, but the bad guy comes in, gives his 10 min speech and they go back, and then get use the help of the "nice robot" to do it all again. And the climax is just getting Trinity.

Then they get Neo, we get cheap revival of the dojo scene from the first film, and we get like 20 minutes of exposition that literally serve zero purpose for the rest of the film. The survivors lock him up, but he gets princess carried out of the "cell" by the side characters.

The movie starts with the goal of finding Neo and waking him up *again*. They do a bunch of flashback shots from the previous movies to the point I just got sick of it, like, we get it, this is a sequel, stuff happened before this.
The first act is "decent", the second act is boring as hell and the third act is "decent". The new characters get nothing but the cheapest example of an arc if they even get it.

Anyways, the film is objectively pretty good, I did enjoy the bigger emphasis on Mina and Dracula's relationship since it had little dimension in the book. I find the dramatic style choice to be very honoring to the original material.

This isn't film criticism, this is social and personal criticism. I am a big fan of Dracula and of Gary Oldman's performance, and so, it would've been easy for me to tear up at the end of it. But I was unable to connect with it, because his image was tainted with these factors.
The vampire myth carries inherent sensuality, and Coppola gave us some of that, but he also overindulged in the porno display of it with the characters of Dracula's brides and Lucy.
The way they handled Lucy's character specially bothered me. They reduced her to a male fantasy of sorts. They emphasised her sexuality for their own enjoyment, only to then condemned her as a whore.
